<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Gap In The Bridge<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 22, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> *NOTE: While not all of the cards in this article have been revealed on Decipher&#39;s web site, they have been shown around on site like DeckTech, Gameplayer&#39;s Network, and other areas. If their text is not clear in the article, and you can&#39;t find them elsewhere, I&#39;ll point you to where they&#39;re gotten from*<br />
<br />
The Balrog is big. Not meaning to want to state the obvious, but he&#8217;s huge. Able to overwhelm any character (if they have no weapons or other cards affected them) single handily and has the ability to destroy almost key strategies that the fellowship holds dear to them with his myriad of support cards: archery, Boromir with Armor, Gandalf, burden protection, etc&#8230; However, he&#8217;s not simply just a giant obstacle awaiting you at site five; he&#8217;s an entire strategy unto himself, with both Durin&#8217;s Bane and the Flame of Udun having very different and very distinct strategies related to them. However, for the fellowship, it truly does boil down to this: your facing one big freakin&#8217; minion. <br />
<br />
THE BIG FREAKIN&#8217; MINION PRINCABLE (AKA: HOW TO FEED A CAVE TROLL):<br />
<br />
The Balrog is a distant cousins of several minions of Middle-Earth, primarily the Cave Troll, Lurtz, and the Witch King. You know the type: costs quite a bit of twilight, but the shadow players definitely gets their bang for their buck. High strength and vitality, fierceness, and/or damage +1. These are basically the minions that the free people can&#8217;t fight. Sure, Aragorn with his Sword can beat up on almost all minions, but unless you&#8217;re willing to waste all your available strength bonuses in hand for one skirmish, you&#8217;re most likely not going to win against a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion. <br />
<br />
From the fellowship player&#8217;s point of view, it&#8217;s important to realize that the best way to play against Big Freakin&#8217; Minions is defense. If you can&#8217;t beat it, avoid it. Through and through, the best way to do this is simply pull out the lamb&#8217;s blood, paint a member of your fellowship in it, and offer them as a sacrifice. Ever wonder why Thrarin is so popular in almost ever deck? It&#8217;s because for a one time cost of one, you get a character who simply sits around and doesn&#8217;t come into play until you need him to. Basically, for one card slot in a deck, you got a freebie member of your fellowship who won&#8217;t add twilight when he moves, but can skirmish with the best (worst?) of them. Sam and Pippin serve this same concept: after they heal off wounds and/or burdens, they&#8217;re worthless. In fact, in Pippin&#8217;s case, most of the time he hurts the fellowship: he&#8217;ll add twilight when you move and could make you vulnerable to cards like Savagery To Match Their Numbers or Ulaire Enquea. As soon as Pippin takes off that wound that is between Legolas&#8217;s exhaustion and death, kill him.<br />
<br />
Outside of serving up the sacrifice, always have a few trick cards handy: Aragorn&#8217;s Bow to knock out that Lurtz or big twilight Ulaire Neyla (sure, three wounds on Aragorn hurts, but it&#8217;s better then facing a damage +1 Lurtz or Neyla twice), Hobbit Stealth, Hobbit Intuition, or O Elibereth! Gilthoniel! to just simply hide (though watch out for the counters), or even someone like Boromir, he just keep taking punishment until he&#8217;s dead. As a free player, it has to be your priority to not only be able to kill those small and medium sized minions with your companions, but also keep everyone (especially the Ring-bearer) safe from those you can&#8217;t hurt.<br />
<br />
<br />
If you&#8217;re a shadow player and are using a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion, keep in mind that most players already use the above defenses. You Cannot Pass!, Servant of the Secret Fire, and Gandalf wielding his Staff are common enough where you must realize that the point behind a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion isn&#8217;t really to kill anything. Sure, it&#8217;s nice to maybe get that Witch King out at site three against an ill prepared fellowship, but even then you won&#8217;t overwhelm an Aragorn. No, the point of a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion is to wear down the free player. Look, if Gandalf wants to use his Staff to stop from battling Lurtz, that&#8217;s OK. You&#8217;ve just caused two wounds, which is what Lurtz would have caused anyways. While you may not have been able to play your Savagery To Match Their Numbers to kill him, you&#8217;ve just prevented Gandalf from using his Staff later on down the road. <br />
<br />
Same thing goes for Pippin and Thrarin: yes, it&#8217;s annoying to see your fierce Witch King kill nothing then someone who is suppose to bite the bullet, but they&#8217;re gone. Kaput. No more. If you do this at site four or five, then more to you: that means they won&#8217;t have these defense later on. Basically, it boils down to the Big Freakin&#8217; Minion&#8217;s purpose is the following: cause them to play cards, kill companions/allies, or exert for things like Aragorn&#8217;s Bow which they weren&#8217;t planning to earlier. This allows you to swoop down and let your other minions have a bigger impact later on.<br />
<br />
THE BALROG (FREE PLAYER&#8216;S POINT OF VIEW -- AKA: RUN AWAY!):<br />
<br />
OK, your asking yourself now: Sure the Cave Troll is big, but this is the Balrog we&#8217;re talking about! As the shadow player, you&#8217;ll always, 99% of the time have the twilight and ability to play him (if he is in your deck). The only exception is something extreme, like playing two Deft In Their Movements with all the site subtracting things out. It&#8217;s unlikely such a set up will a) ever happen (that&#8217;s a lot of cards out by turn three or four) and b) be done successfully (either you got a lot of people sitting around during the regroup phase and double moving will be out of the question or you won&#8217;t have played much at all and the pool makes up for the site number loss). Folks, making it so you don&#8217;t have six twilight at the Bridge isn&#8217;t going to happen often -- you&#8217;re going to face the Balrog if your opponent wants you to. <br />
<br />
From the free player&#8217;s perspective, it&#8217;s absolutely foolish to not prepare for the Balrog. I mean, if you know that they&#8217;ll have the twilight and ability to play it, why would you think any other way? If they don&#8217;t use it, good for you, but it&#8217;s too big of a risk to play Russian Roulette with your fellowship. However, the key to beating the Balrog isn&#8217;t as much at site five as it is at site four. You heard that right: I&#8217;m not insinuating that you&#8217;ll be foolish enough to give a player twelve twilight at any site four (if you are, well&#8230; don&#8217;t), but how you distribute your wounds from skirmishes and archery is going to reflect how well you&#8217;re going to do against the Balrog. In other words, there&#8217;s very few things that you&#8217;ll face at site four that should warrant you using Gandalf&#8217;s Staff or sending Thrarin or Pippin into a skirmish for. Yes, The Watcher in the Water surrounded by its tentacles (though, how they have enough twilight to do that is beyond me) is a pain, but put the three wounds on Aragorn and move on -- he won&#8217;t follow. That non-roaming Orthnac Assassin at Hollin is a pain, but let Arwen and Boromir take a couple of wounds. You know you&#8217;re very likely to be facing a (minimum) seventeen strength, damage +1, fierce minion next turn, why waste cards in other situations when you could just take wounds?<br />
<br />
The other key to diminishing the effects of the Balrog is the twilight pool you give them, especially against Flame of Udun. Yes, they&#8217;ll always have the six to get him out, but if you only give off one more when you move thanks to No Strangers To The Shadows on Aragorn and Arwen, they&#8217;ll only have enough for his Whip, but not Final Cry. Against Moria, its imperative to give off almost nothing. DO NOT PLAY CARDS AT SITE FOUR! I can&#8217;t reiterate this enough, there&#8217;s almost nothing that&#8217;s worth putting out if it has a twilight cost. Yes, they can still play their eight twilight costing Flame of Udun at the Bridge thanks to Runners and just twilight from your moving (Frodo will always add one), but if you drop Boromir, thinking his ability to not be overwhelmed will help out, you could be in a world of trouble when they feed off that twilight to drop a Goblin Scavengers to grab a Schimitar for their Runner. Suddenly, you&#8217;re facing three minions over two. Having to go up against the Balrog is difficult enough, but if you give them the twilight to swarm, you&#8217;re in trouble. <br />
<br />
Of course, there&#8217;s many cards that can help ease the pain of the Balrog&#8217;s wrath. You Cannot Pass! is excellent since you&#8217;ll be able to just throw a sacrificial lamb in front of him and move on. Pippin and Thrarin can go in to 90% of the decks there are and stealth cards still work (though watch out for Final Cry). Of course, as said above in the Big Freakin&#8217; Minion principle, the Balrog is still doing his job by causing you to waste cards instead of holding them for the next four sites that you must face.<br />
<br />
THE BALROG, DURIN&#8217;S BANE (AKA: WHY CAN&#8217;T HE PLAY NICE?)<br />
<br />
I&#8217;m holding fairly steadfast on to the opinion that almost all non-Moria decks should use Durin&#8217;s Bane. Yes, they may give you a giant twilight pool and you can beat them down with that Lurtz and Troop of Uruk-Hai in your hand, inflicting more wounds than the Balrog would, but when they move past the Bridge, you&#8217;ll still have them in your hand unless you discard them at some point. Since one of the main purposes of a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion is to cause them to use up cards that they were going to save, the Balrog can accomplish this nicely for almost any deck he is put into. Granted, it will almost be handing them a double move on a silver platter (since the Balrog can&#8217;t follow), but the possibility to make them have to use up their resources to prevent death or waste cards like Pippin and Tharin before your main skirmishershimmer can be worth your while.<br />
<br />
THE BALROG, FLAME OF UDUN (AKA: SERVED ON HAND AND FOOT)<br />
<br />
The Flame of Udun basic concept is still the same as Durin&#8217;s Bane: it&#8217;s still unlikely that you&#8217;ll ever actually kill anything, but he&#8217;ll wear down the fellowship enough where your other minions are able to pick them off. However, unlike Durin&#8217;s Bane, its direct: if pulled off correctly, your going to face a swarm in addition to a Big Freakin&#8217; Minion, meaning while the Balrog will draw off your defenses, the rest of Moria will eat you alive.<br />
<br />
Using Flame of Udun correctly is a bit more difficult. Unlike his counterpart, he thrives off of a large twilight pool. While you&#8217;ll almost always have the eight to work with to play him, you must first be able to spot a Moria Orc to use him. The Goblin Runner (who adds to the pool) or Moria Scout (plays for free against Elves) are the best choices here. However, this is Moria: you want to add to the pool and just beat them up. While the Balrog will take up most of the twilight, with only one or two Goblin Armories out (play them that turn -- don&#8217;t give Albert Dreary or Sleep, Caradhas the opportunity to cancel them before you can use them), a single Goblin Scavenger can pay for himself. In other words, all Moria decks should probably use the Flame of Udun over Durin&#8217;s Bane, but unless a player is truly foolish enough to give off a ton of twilight, it&#8217;s unlikely that you&#8217;ll get as large a swarm as you could without him (though having that seventeen strength, fierce, and damage +1 minion makes up for that). However, just forcing your opponent to have to consider assignment against more than just one minion is worth the cost alone.<br />
<br />
SUPPORT CARDS (AKA: YOU MEAN HE&#8217;S NOT BIG ENOUGH AS IS?!)<br />
<br />
Using support cards for either Balrog can be a bit tricky. On one hand, he has some of the most powerful cards in the game, but, on the other, your opponent will most likely never see him for more then one site for one turn. In other words, overwhelming Pippin by five times his strength with the Whip of Many Thongs and Sword isn&#8217;t much different then just overwhelming him normally. Also, even if you do run into a opponent who is sending up his Aragorn or Gandalf to skirmish the Balrog, throw a couple of Whips and a couple of Final Cries in your deck will hurt later on in the way of card advantage: your going to end up drawing cards that are automatically worthless. However, if you can get some of the Balrog-based combos to pull off, it can be worth the effort. A list of support cards and uses:<br />
<br />
-- The Balrog&#8217;s Sword: I&#8217;m not a particular fan of this artifact mainly because while it may help in overwhelming Aragorn or Gandalf if they&#8217;re carrying their respective weapons, in many cases it is simply over kill and is weak compared to the Whip/Final Cry, especially since no player will send a key companion to skirmish the Balrog with his Sword unless they have some sort of trick up their sleeve.<br />
<br />
-- Dark Fire: Bad. Really bad. Since you have to play it during the shadow phase, it basically means Gandalf will be backing off from skirmishing. More so, since it&#8217;s a condition, it&#8217;s fairly worthless, since Albert Dreary or Sleep can cancel it. Of course, you can&#8217;t even guarantee your opponent will be playing Gandalf to begin with. <br />
<br />
-- Fill With Fear: Best Balrog related card there is, in my opinion. First off, it is free and can be played at any time (read: don&#8217;t have to spot the Balrog to play it) so you can at least get it out of your hand. Against a dedicated archery deck, there&#8217;s really no better counter outside of Spies of Saruman. Sure, Durin&#8217;s Bane already skips the archery phase but (a) Flame of Udun doesn&#8217;t (nothing hurts more then watching those one vitality, strength ten Scavengers and Scimitars bite the dust before they can skirmish) and (b) getting rid of Aragorn&#8217;s Bow for the cost of a single exertion on a five vitality minions is worth it. Sure, it may be back but they won&#8217;t have it if they double move and if they discarded any copies earlier (or it&#8217;s on the bottom on their draw deck), well, tough luck.<br />
<br />
-- Final Cry: On first gander, it seems very powerful: a character skirmishing the Balrog with his Whip of Many Thongs is going to take two wounds, period. Its weakness, however, is in the fact that it is very conditional and if you don&#8217;t draw the Whip to go with it, you&#8217;ve wasted two card slots. Again, if the Balrog is only skirmishing Pippin or Thrarin, you&#8217;re going to end up with a handful of wasted cards, even if he serves his purpose of wearing down the fellowship&#8217;s defenses. Useful in many circumstances, like against a Gandalf bearing his Staff or simply just to get in two free wounds and kill off Aragorn or Boromir, but the possibility of wasting card slots sets a dangerous precedent for the rest of your deck and building half of your shadow deck off of one site can be extremely risky and a waste of card slots.<br />
<br />
-- Must Do Without Hope: Ladies and gentlemen, I present to you Ulaire Balrog. Must Do Without Hope is a &#8220;must have&#8221; in many Nazgul and Sauron decks, especially the new Twilight Nazgul decks which focus on corrupting the Ring-bearer. While I don&#8217;t suggest stocking four of them (see above about relying on one site), it&#8217;s an extremely powerful card for an extremely powerful deck type at a very minimal cost. While it&#8217;s doubtful this alone will corrupt the Ring-bearer, it may make a player want to hold onto their Sam a bit longer so they can heal him to take off burdens. This, however, can almost be as good as removing one of their shields: by piling up the burdens on Frodo, the free people&#8217;s player will feel much more reluctant to use him as a shield against the Balrog for when they have to meet up against the Twilight Nazgul at site six on. Putting them in a position where they must use someone else to skirmish or lose a powerful burden removing strategy is a strategic position to be in.<br />
<br />
-- Power And Terror: Not much here since it can&#8217;t be combined with the Bridge text and it will require a handful of Moria Orcs to get out the Balrog at site four. Also, a single Sting or Galmdring will dash any hopes of that site four Balrog.<br />
<br />
-- Whip of Many Thongs: Basically allows the Balrog to wear down Boromir, Lord of Gondor hiding behind his Armor to prevent any significant damage. While you still won&#8217;t be able to overwhelm him, you&#8217;ll make him fairly worthless in skirmishes from there on out. Helps against Dwarves who may rely on their Dwarven Armor (or Gimli with his Helm) to keep them safe, but if it is going to find any use, it&#8217;s going to be with Final Cry (see above on the risks for that strategy).<br />
<br />
In conclusion, The Balrog is an extremely powerful minion, capable of wrecking havoc. However, his most powerful uses (and counters) are much more subtle. You won&#8217;t win the game at site five, but you&#8217;ll make their journey from there on out much more dangerous. As a free player, it is important to prepare for this and know that its going to be coming by stocking the cards and just playing smart. Either way, the Balrog is just one of many potent components that Mines of Moria adds to the risk and excitement of this game. <br />
Avoid the fire (if you can),<br />
<br />
Drew<br />
